**Today's pick** — _NatureBench breaks the agent, and VCs back the harness anyway_:

- **Twitter Pulse** lead: NatureBench (arXiv 2606.24530, June 23) — strongest of 10 frontier agent configurations (Claude Opus 4.7, GPT-5.5, Gemini 3.5, Kimi K2.6, DeepSeek V4 Pro, GLM-5.1, Qwen 3.7 Max, etc.) beats published Nature-family SOTA on only 17.8% of 90 tasks at g>0.1. 45.1% of failures = wrong method choice. Quotable take: agents do "methodological translation, not genuine scientific invention." Three of the six benchmark domains (cellular omics, protein biology, biomedical modeling) anchor the number directly to Ollie's bench. Companion: _Are We Ready For An Agent-Native Memory System?_ (2606.24775).
- **Money Moves**: June 24 was an agentic-AI funding day — seven rounds, ~$362.5M combined (Assort Health $120M, Taktile $110M, Hang Ten $32M, Attention $30M, Runlayer $30M, Coval $28M, Seltz $12.5M). The three pure-infrastructure rounds — governance, eval, retrieval — are the more telling signal. Open-source counter: Databricks released Omnigient under Apache 2.0; Matei Zaharia + Reynold Xin on Latent Space's "Why the Frontier Ecosystem must be Open" (June 24).
- **Deep Cut**: Dwarkesh Patel's solo essay "The data black hole at the center of AI" (June 19) — million-fold sample-efficiency gap; data, not architecture, is the moat. Patel's frame predicts NatureBench's failure mode and reframes the funding day as data-acquisition plays.
- **Wrap**: Watch which of the seven agentic rounds names task-specific trajectory data as a use of proceeds.

